posts.name: Tori Dell
posts.cooked:
As I was creating my team’s Constants.java for this season, I was split on the naming conventions we should use for the constants. Whenever I program outside of FRC , I always use UPPERCASE_SNAKE_CASE, but I haven’t seen many instances of that in the FRC team’s code. In previous years, we have used mostly camelCase except for PID constants (kP, kI, kD, etc.). I also know that Google’s Java Style Guide promotes UPPERCASE_SNAKE_CASE.

I’m wondering what other teams generally do for this, and I would love to hear people’s thoughts.

posts.name: neev dadhania
posts.cooked:
i think UPPERCASE_SNAKE_CASE is like the most prominent way of naming constants universally, which is why it seems to be the most popular way in your poll.

but to address the kPrefix folks, it seems that wpi’s style guide tells to use the kPrefix format for some reason (section 5.2.4 if youre curious)

I believe this is a subsection of Hungarian notation, that also dictates to use m_ for member variables. However, m_ prefixing makes intuitive sense, but k isn’t nearly as intuitive as capitalized snake case.

posts.name: neev dadhania
posts.cooked:
NathanZhou:

pinYinBianLiangMing

what does it mean? google translate isnt helping me

Do whatever you want as long as it’s consistent. And it isn’t kConstantName. (Code should be close to reading aloud; I don’t want to say k-constant-name, I want to say constant name).

Personally, and as a team, and really as an industry, the tendency is very much towards UPPERCASE_SNAKE_CASE. But what really matters is you do the same thing in your whole codebase.

posts.name: Eric Ward
posts.cooked:
I dislike code shouting at me. I don’t see the reason constants should have a different naming convention from any local variable. We usually place them in a namespace anyway (e.g. “ElevatorConstants”).

The only naming schemes I like to differentiate are typenames, member variables, and everything else. Prefer not to prefix with m_ or k because it slows down autocomplete. For member variables, I really like just suffixing with an underscore. Classes I like PascalCase.

posts.name: Tori Dell
posts.cooked:
bathtubed:

I dislike code shouting at me. I don’t see the reason constants should have a different naming convention from any local variable. We usually place them in a namespace anyway (e.g. “ElevatorConstants”).

I agree. Especially for a file like Constants.java that is just constants, using all caps feels like the code is screaming in pain. We also make sure to not make a flat import such as import ...Constants.*; which makes sure any constant is identified as a constant because it is accessed as Constants.constant .

bathtubed:

Prefer not to prefix with m_ or k because it slows down autocomplete.

I’ve actually heard some people saying that the prefixes are a benefit for autocomplete because it allows you to just type m_ or k and see all members or constants of a class. I haven’t personally found this super useful, but I can see why some people would.

This is the only one that is difficult to read for me. The others are fine. I find this jarring because it mixes the older style of names using underscores with the newish fad of lowercase everything.

posts.name: Eric Ward
posts.cooked:
LordOfFrogs:

I’ve actually heard some people saying that the prefixes are a benefit for autocomplete because it allows you to just type m_ or k and see all members or constants of a class. I haven’t personally found this super useful, but I can see why some people would.

That’s fair, there’s 2 schools of thought. When you are relying on intellisense to search an index of symbols, its better to have prefixing in narrowing levels of specificity as you type. (so, kElevatorGearReduction better than GearReductionElevator ).

In the case I’m thinking of, I’m trying to type things in the fewest number of keystrokes possible, so I want to symbol I’m typing to be unambiguous to autocomplete the soonest possible. But honestly, I think the former is a more respectable goal.

I sort of wish autocomplete in IDEs functioned like it does in terminals where hitting tab completes to the first ambiguous point.

We sort of get the benefit of this using namespacing.

For example Constants::Elevator::gear_reduction vs Constants::elevator_gear_reduction . The latter can be very tiring to work with when there’s also elevator_kp , elevator_mass , elevator_max_speed , etc.

posts.name: Aaron Zheng
posts.cooked: Yes. For our team, we use m_PascalCase notation as well as kPascalCase .
